IrCipuYhJZaoSoLCassY8A.text: West siders familiar with famed food truck Tacos Tijuana will likely walk into Tacos Calafia feeling like the menu here is an echo of the Tijuana food truck.  And indeed owner Adolfo Torres Jr operated Tacos Tijuana before branching out and opening this brick and mortar.  I was unaware of this before stopping in, but a Phoenix New Times article on the wall of the restaurant pointed out this fact.  This gave me supreme confidence I'd made the right choice coming here on a Friday during lunch.  You'll find Calafia on the northeast corner of 83rd Avenue and Thunderbird.  You can't miss the place once you're in the parking lot.  There's no fancy signage, just a giant TACOS banner hanging out front.  Walk inside, order at the main counter and they call your number at the pickup window when its ready.  A lengthy salsa bar is right up front to decorate your food as you please and the seating inside is mostly no frills folding chairs and plastic tables with a few high tables mixed in.  Altogether I'd guess they can pack in 60 or so at once.  And today they damn near did.  Firefighters, contractors, construction workers, and suits were all in line ordering up big group portions for dining in and to go.  Fortunately the line moves fairly quick.  In addition to tacos, they offer quesadillas, nachos, vampiros, and mulitas.  But today I elected to keep it simple and order 4 tacos on corn tortillas.  Each taco containing one of their four meat offerings:  Carne Asada (steak), Al Pastor (pork), Pollo (chicken), and Cabeza (beef cheek).  Also got a small horchata.  And yes, they honor the free taco Yelp check-in.   Total cost for everything including tax and the free check-in came to a very budget friendly $8.  I dressed my tacos at the salsa bar with some cilantro, onion, guac, and a hint of salsa verde.  The carne asada and pollo were perfect with just the perfect amount of char and seasoning.  The cabeza was a new one for me, but I really liked it.  Tasted like eating a tender beef short rib in taco form.  The al pastor on the other hand?  A little disappointing.  The flavor was okay, but honestly when I bit into the taco it was oil overload.  The Al Pastor I had at Tacos Tijuana were amazing so I know Adolfo and his crew know how to make these right, so I'm guessing today the sauce was just a misfire.  Better luck next time on those (I hope).  All things considered, I can't knock Calafia for the prices or the quality of their meats.  And dining in a comfortably air conditioned space has almost certainly paid off for Adolfo's business when dining al fresco in the middle of summer is less than ideal.  So good on him for getting a permanent space to call his own.  Next time I'll dive deeper into his other Mexican staples (especially the Mulitas).  Super prices, super simple menu, (mostly) super food.  Proof that if you do the simple things right, you'll get a line of loyal fans dozens deep like there was today.

nFfajH6BkrU0awbTwmz5bA.text: This place is definitely up there. Since moving from LA, I've been looking for the perfect carne asada nachos. I've had basically all other options in Phoenix and wasn't that impressed. I'd actually begun just making my own at home because I need every element (cheese, meat, toppings, type of chips, red salsa) to be just perfect to cure my nacho nostalgia. On that note, sometimes having them made for me, without the time and mess, is a better option. I came across this place by chance because I was in the area. They looked like Tacos Tijuana (which is still my favorite Tijuana style taco in Arizona)  but had the element of actual options. On numerous occasions I've longed for Tacos Tijuana to offer nachos and burritos but alas they keep their menu small (and just delightful). It turns out this place is owned by someone that came from Tacos Tijuana so seeing nachos on the menu made me hopeful. Now the review: they let you put toppings on at a full toppings bar (including guac, yeah you heard me) and that made me very happy. I ordered extra cheese because I like my nachos drenched and when I dipped my finger in the cheese was kind of disappointed. The lack of flavor was quite apparent but I liked the consistency (yeah, totally a nacho snob) so I continued to add my toppings. Once I actually ate them I realized the cheese was perfect. Their meat and toppings  are so damn flavorful that the cheese fit right in. At that point I assumed that if their cheese had been too flavorful it might have distracted from that delicious meat. I get it now and am very pleased. I will definitely be back for them if in the area but it is quite a drive from me, so for now I'll continue to make my own and find reasons to drive out there.   Their free taco at check-in was a tad skimpy but I'm assuming that's because it's free. But I guess that's NACHO problem.

T5fMHXsrujiZJhN_tWrEKQ.text: Best taco place in peoria as I always say. They do have other options but I unfortunately wasn't able to try them.  When you receive your order, they have a salad bar available for you to load up your tacos. Their guacamole as well as their salsa are absolutely amazing and if you can stand the heat, I highly recommend the red salsa because it has an amazing flavor unlike most salsas where the heat just takes over and completely ruins the meal. TlEeWgITrtqywAWuV1U_9w.text: These are True Mexican street tacos so if you're looking for Americanized versions of the taco, this isn't your place. We went there on Friday at 8:40 and the place was packed- I mean literally could not find a chair and the dining area is huge by taco-place standards. The options are minimal; chicken, steak, pork and beef cheek on corn or flour tortillas. They also offer quesadillas, mulitas (basically a quesadilla but with corn tortillas, and a few others.   The pros: We tried the steak, chicken, pork and beef cheek tacos. Everyone liked the pork (el pastor) tacos. The tortillas are hand made and delicious. I hate flour tortillas- literally cannot stand them. Tried these and they are the first flour tortillas I've ever liked. They're so thin and delicious. There is a large taco bar for salsa toppings and the horchata is great as well.   The cons: I think there was a bit of a hang up in the kitchen, it took us about 35 minutes to get our tacos. Considering they are tortillas and meat and you do the toppings yourself that felt like a long wait. I honestly could not recommend the chicken taco. The chicken tastes like poor quality or poor cutting on the cooks side. There is a lot of gristle and tendon in the chicken taco- we had three of them and every chicken taco had tendon in it- not appetizing.

cJhg0Wy11jeraDSQi7l6sA.text: Hoo boy, I discovered Tacos Calafia a few months ago, and man is it difficult to stay away. The tacos are so cheap, and so delicious, every time I drive through the Thunderbird/83rd intersection, I find myself racking my brain for any reason to stop and get tacos.   Tacos Calafia taco ranking:  5 - Nopales vegetarian tacos - not for me, but if you need veggie tacos, I mean, they have something, that's nice 4 - Chicken tacos - just great grilled chicken, juicy and crispy, but I could make this at home 3 - Carne Asada - you know you make great tacos when carne asada gets 3rd place!! 2 - Cabeza - Cabeza means 'head,' I don't know exactly which head cuts they use, probably some tongue, maybe some other ones, but it's kind of a juicy  raised beef mixture, a unique and delicious taco 1 - Al Pastor - spicy pork, speared with a pineapple topped spit, just the outside crispy bits served to you, this is the star of the show.   Homemade corn or flour tortillas, you can't go wrong, they're both great - I think I slightly prefer the flour, but corn is nipping at flour's heels. Get a classic taco truck beverage - Jarritos Mandarin, or Sangia Senorial, or horchata - then head over to the toppings bar. They have salsas, and tub o' guac, but my recommendation is to skip that and just load up on onions for crunch,  cilantro for freshness, and limes for the acidity - save that salsa for chips, the salsa heat drowns out the spices in the two best tacos, Al Pastor and Cabeza.   Then dig in, I usually get 5 tacos and a drink for about $10, and I can sit outside or inside. The best bite is an Al Pastor taco with onions, cilantro, and lime - Calafia Mafia!!!

GkpADkY7y51y8bnxjfE1lg.text: I think one of the things everybody can agree on is that tacos are great. The only dissent may be the place to get tacos. Tacos Calafia is a great option for tacos, especially when it comes to value. It's a pretty crowded market out here since it's a major city in the southwest, but overall I would recommend this place.   First things first, the price is great. $2 for tacos with cheese, and $1.75 for tacos without cheese. I usually go for the carne asada, but they also have pollo asado, pastor, and tacos vampiros. $7 for a plate of 4 fills you up and is a good value for what the quality of them. Steak is always cooked tenderly, and it's a pleasurable eating experience. Also they have a great salsa bar too, with the hot salsa having a lot of heat to it and the guacamole is plentiful. That's about all you need at a taco shop.  This place is worth a visit if you want to get down on some reasonably priced, quality tacos. Sure there are flashier places, but they're a far drive. Why put off jamming out on your taco Tuesday instead of going here?

2acAPaFv9GgTlA9jocAZ3g.text: It's no lie that there's definitely not a shortage of taco options on the Westside. That's definitely not an issue. The problem is, however, that few of these places are worth recommending as anything more than just a quick fix with only a few exceptions to note.  Recently opened Tacos Calafia has the potential to change all that. I'm fairly certain that it's owned by the same people that run Tacos Tijuana, only the menu is slightly expanded.   The building used to be home to a sorta-steakhouse called Carvers and probably a few other businesses over the years. It's a pretty big space for a simple taco joint, so you'll have plenty of different seating options available. Calafia specializes in your traditional street tacos that are reasonably priced and executed surprisingly well. They also offer mulitas, vampiros, and the usual quesadillas.  My girlfriend ordered a mulita and two asada tacos. I ordered two pastor and one asada. For some reason, they messed up my order and brought out two asada. Since I didn't feel like battling through the line to complain, I just ordered a couple of extra pastor tacos to sample after I had finished. I also threw in a cheese quesadilla as well.  The asada tacos are fine, although pretty much the same as what you'd find at most places that know what they're doing. Their pastor, however, was excellent - completely living up to the praise that it's receiving from the few reviews this place currently has. I'd still recommend sampling both, but the pastor is clearly the superior of the two in terms of flavor. Additionally, you can have chicken, although I'll save that for another day.  The quesadilla was fine while the mulita actually impressed both my girlfriend and I. It's a great beefier alternative to just the regular tacos. They also were selling champurrado (Mexican hot chocolate) that we both really enjoyed. Although I'm not entirely sure if the item is a permanent staple, it damn well should be!  Are there better tacos in Phoenix? Of course. But in the immediate area, I feel this is probably one of the better options available.  Highly recommended!

I am happy they carry coke products to have with the tacos, however their drink machine is very high. Short people may have a hard time reaching it. In all, I would return for the carne asada and a coke. Skip the elote and just find a guy in the Peoria streets for that.
